  "prompt": "What evolved into Homo sapiens?",
  "response": "Homo sapiens, our species, evolved from earlier hominins. The evolutionary lineage leading to modern humans includes several species within the genus Homo. Key ancestors include:\n\n1. **Australopithecus**: This genus existed around 4 to 2 million years ago and includes species like Australopithecus afarensis (e.g., the famous \"Lucy\"). They were bipedal but still had adaptations for climbing.\n\n2. **Homo habilis**: Often considered one of the earliest members of the genus Homo, Homo habilis emerged around 2.4 to 1.4 million years ago. They are thought to have used simple stone tools.\n\n3. **Homo erectus**: Existing from about 1.9 million years ago to as recently as 110,000 years ago, Homo erectus is believed to have been more similar to modern humans in body proportions and is associated with more advanced tool use and possibly the control of fire.\n\n4. **Neanderthals (Homo neanderthalensis)**: They lived in Europe and parts of Asia until about 40,000 years ago and shared a common ancestor with modern humans. Genetic evidence suggests that there was some interbreeding between Neanderthals and early modern humans.\n\n5. **Denisovans**: A relatively recently discovered group of archaic humans known from fossil evidence found in Siberia. They also interacted and interbred with modern humans.\n\nHomo sapiens first appeared in Africa around 300,000 years ago and gradually spread out, replacing or interbreeding with other hominin species as they migrated to different parts of the world. The evolution of Homo sapiens involved a complex interplay of genetic, environmental, and cultural factors.",
